\begin_layout Section
Bilinear interpolation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
\noindent

\series medium
It is an interpolation method to determine the intensity of a target point.
 After doing target-to-source mapping, we cannot always assure that the
 source co-ordinates are perfect integers.
 In most cases, they will have fractional parts and hence, will lie within
 the square enclosed by the neighbouring four integer co-ordinates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
\noindent

\series medium
Sometimes, the source co-ordinates may even completely lie outside the image
 dimensions (In which case, an intensity of 0 is given to the target point).

\series default
 
\series medium
But assuming the source co-ordinates are fractional and lie within the image,
 we have the following interpolation formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I(x,y)=(1-a)(1-b)I(x',y')+(1-a)(b)I(x',y'+1)+(a)(1-b)I(x'+1,y')+(a)(b)I(x'+1,y'+1)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 is the floor of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

 is the floor of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Pictorially, this interpolation method is represented as shown below:
\end_layout

